at|So far our study of opening leads has focused on notrump contracts. It is time to turn our attention to selecting an opening lead when there is a trump suit. There are some similarities between leading against a trump contract and leading against notrump. In particular, the basic purpose of the opening lead, to put the defense in a position to defeat the declarer's contract, is the same regardless of what the contract happens to be.

The following principles, which we learned are reliable guidelines for selecting an opening lead against a notrump contract, also apply when there is a trump suit:^^
|
qx|1.2|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ Leading a suit that your partner has bid is usually a good thing to do. }

|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ Leading a suit that your opponents have bid is usually a bad thing to do. }

|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ Leading a suit headed by a strong honor sequence (like KQJ) is usually a good thing to do. }
^-
Also, there is the one guiding principle that applies not only to opening leads against notrump contracts and opening leads against trump contracts, but also to just about all aspects of the game of bridge:

|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Your judgment is more valuable that any set of guidelines! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


tb||


nt|^b@2^z@3
On some deals, the presence of a trump suit can add a whole new dimension to the process of selecting an opening lead. For example:

|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{Sometimes you should lead a short suit (a singleton or doubleton) against a trump contract
in an attempt to score a trick (or several tricks) with a ruff. There are no ruffs at notrump!}

|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ On some deals the best opening lead for the defense is from the trump suit itself! 
 It goes without saying that you will never lead a trump against a notrump contract! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


at|When selecting an opening lead against a notrump contract, the fundamental goal in most cases is to start establishing small cards in a long suit as winners. This is not usually the case when there is a trump suit. The reason is that even if you are able to establish winners in a long suit against a trump contract, the declarer will be able to prevent you from winning tricks in that suit by ruffing.

This does not imply that you should never select a long suit as your opening lead when there is a trump suit. In fact, on many deals a long suit lead will be the best start for the defenders even when there is no hope of eventually winning tricks with the small cards in that suit.

Pay close attention to the example deals that follow. You will see that in some of these deals, the recommended opening lead is exactly the same lead that would be recommended against a notrump contract. On some of the other examples deals, however, the presence of a trump suit makes a big difference to the opening leader (that's you). Get ready to return to the West seat!|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


