|cp||at|In general, it is more difficult to select an effective opening lead against a trump contract than it is against notrump. The reason is that there are more things to consider when there is a trump suit. In particular, the possibility of ruffs, both for the declarer and the defenders, which is not present at notrump tends to complicate all aspects of the play of the cards (including the opening lead).

Still, there are some principles that we learned when we studied opening leads against notrump that also apply when there is a trump suit:

|
pg| ***** 446 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ Leading a suit that your partner has bid is usually a good thing to do. }

|
pg| ***** 447 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ Leading a suit that your opponents have bid is usually a bad thing to do. }

|
pg| ***** 448 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ Leading a suit headed by a strong honor sequence (like KQJ) is usually a good thing to do. }

|
pg| ***** 449 ***** |


at|^-Finally, do not forget the following guideline which applies to so many aspects of bridge (including selecting an opening lead against any contract):

|
pg| ***** 450 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Your judgment is more valuable that any set of guidelines! }

|
pg| ***** 451 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
If the difference between selecting an opening lead against a trump contract and doing so against notrump could be summarized in one sentence, that sentence might read like this:

|cs|1|at|^-{ Selecting your longest suit as your opening lead, a good strategy against 
 notrump, is not nearly as attractive a proposition when there is a trump suit. }

|
pg| ***** 452 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ The reason is that the declarer will be able to use the trump suit to 
 prevent you from winning tricks with your small cards in your long suits. }

|
pg| ***** 453 ***** |


