You should lead a trump. Against a grand slam you should always lead passively, regardless of whether or not there is a trump suit. Unless the opponents have made a mistake, they would not be trying to win all 13 tricks in a spade contract if they had a potential trump loser. As such, a trump opening lead rates to give nothing away (and that is what being passive is all about).

The opponents' bidding sounds very confident, but perhaps you will be able to win a trick with one of your Queens. Leading away from a Queen, however, would greatly reduce your chances of being able to win a trick with that card. It is best to let the declarer play the side suits for himself.

The whole point of making an aggressive opening lead is to try to establish winners that you will be able to cash when the defense regains the lead. When the contract is a grand slam this reason for leading aggressively does not apply. If you happen to regain the lead, you will have won a trick and defeated the contract - you don't need to have any established winners for the defense to be a success.
