^-{ Standard leads against suit contracts }
^-
|fp||at||cp||at|It has already been mentioned that, from most holdings, the standard opening lead against a trump contract is exactly the same as it would be against notrump. In this topic we will investigate holdings in which the standard opening lead varies on the basis of whether or not there is a trump suit.

If you are not feeling confident about which card to lead from various holdings against notrump, it is a good idea to go back and review that topic before you read this one!

|
pg| ***** 533 ***** |


at|Recall that when the contract is notrump, the standard opening lead from a long suit headed by an honor sequence is the highest card only if the honor sequence has at least 3 cards in it.

|
pg| ***** 534 ***** |


cs|3|at|^F{|ih|psqjt54|at|} |n#|h|at|^Q{|ih|phqj543|at|}

|ht|o|at|For example, the holding to the left is headed by a 3-card honor sequence (the @SQJ10) so the @SQ is the standard opening lead against notrump. However, the holding on the right is headed by only 2 honors (the @HQJ) so the 4th best card (the @H4) would be the standard opening lead against notrump. |
pg| ***** 535 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3|
cs|3|n#|9|at|^F{|ih|psqjt54|at|} |n#|j|n#|4|at|^Q{|ih|phqj543|at|}

|ht|d|at|When there is a trump suit things are different. Now a 2-card honor sequence is sufficient to lead the highest card in a given suit. With both of the above holdings the standard opening lead would be the Queen against a trump contract.

The @SQ would be the standard lead from the holding on the left regardless of the final contract, but the @HQ would be the standard lead from the holding on the right only if there was a trump suit (otherwise the 4th best @H4 would be the standard lead).

|
pg| ***** 536 ***** |


at|The subject of which card to lead against notrump from a suit headed by the Ace-King was purposely avoided. This issue is more complex than you might think and it will be explored in detail in the third chapter of this program.

However, if you are fortunate enough to be dealt an Ace-King combination when you are on lead against a trump contract there is a simple rule that describes the standard opening lead from such a holding:

|
pg| ***** 537 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Lead the Ace from a holding headed by the Ace-King when you are on opening lead against
 a trump contract unless you hold the Ace-King doubleton. Lead the King in that case. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 538 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
The main difference between standard opening leads against trump contracts and those against notrump involves holdings that do not include any honor cards. Recall that against notrump the standard opening lead from 3 small cards is the highest card and that the standard opening lead from 4 or more small cards is the second highest card.

|
pg| ***** 539 ***** |


cs|3|at|^F{|ih|pd854|at|} ^Q{|ih|pc97532|at|}

In the above examples, the @D8 and the @C7 would be the standard opening leads from these holdings if the contract was notrump.

|
pg| ***** 540 ***** |


at|The question of what the standard opening lead should be from these holdings against a trump contract is more complex and bridge experts have wrestled with this issue since the 1920s. To this day there is no strong consensus as to which cards should represent the standard opening leads from holdings like those shown above.

The holding on the left, that of 3 small cards, is especially controversial. There are plenty of experts who prefer to lead the highest card from such a holding, just like they would against notrump. |
pg| ***** 541 ***** |


at|Some experts would lead the middle card, the @D5, from this holding |
pg| ***** 542 ***** |


at|and yet another group of experts prefer to lead the small card, the @D4 in this case, from 3 small cards. |
pg| ***** 543 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|3|n#|5|at|^B{|ih|pd854|at|} 

|ht|c|at|^G@2We could spend quite a lot of time exploring the relative advantages and disadvantages of leading high, middle, and low from 3 small cards against a trump contract, but there would be little point to this. 

^b@2
The world's leading players have been unable to agree on what should be the standard opening lead from this holding and they have had over 70 years to argue about it. It is therefore unlikely that we are going to come up with a completely satisfying solution to this problem in this program.

|
pg| ***** 544 ***** |


at|Instead, we are just going to make a decision and that will be to lead the lowest of 3 small cards against a trump contract (the @D4 in the holding shown above). The main reason for this decision is that, at the present time, most experts in North America (including the author of this program) prefer to lead the smallest of 3 small cards against a trump contract. 

If, for some reason, you feel strongly that you would rather lead the high or middle card from 3 small cards against trump contracts, there is nothing wrong with that. Just make sure that your partner knows that you are going to do this! 

|
pg| ***** 545 ***** |


at|Remember that the whole point of standard opening leads is to help the partner of the opening leader figure out what holding has been led from. Which card your partnership leads from 3 small cards against a trump contract is relatively unimportant. Always leading the same card from such a holding is very important. If you vary the cards that you lead from this (or any) holding, you will end up with a confused partner!

|
pg| ***** 546 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|3|n#|5|at|^B{|ih|pc97532|at|} 
|ht|b|n#|5|at|^^^^^G@2The question of which card to lead from 4 or more small cards against a trump contract is a little bit less controversial. Some experts prefer to lead the second highest card from such holdings (the @C7 in this example), just as they would against notrump. 
^b@2

|
pg| ***** 547 ***** |


at|Again we could debate forever the merits of leading various cards from this holding, but in the end we would be unlikely to find a completely satisfying answer. Instead we are just going to make a decision and that decision will be to lead the 4th best card from such holdings - the @C3 in the example holding shown above.

|
pg| ***** 548 ***** |


cs|2|at|To summarize:

^-{ Against a trump contract, if you choose to lead from a suit with no honor cards, lead the 
 lowest card from a 3-card suit and lead the 4th best card from a suit with 4 or more cards in it. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 549 ***** |


cs|4|at|And now some good news:

^-{ The standard opening leads against trump contracts from interior sequences, 
 broken suits, and doubletons are the same as what they are against notrump. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 550 ***** |


at|Don't worry if you are finding it difficult to remember all of the standard opening leads from various holdings against trump and notrump contracts. All you need to do is practice a little. It won't take long before you know your standard leads inside out!

|
